    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1981-04-06T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1981-04-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="188"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d188">
                <head>188. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for <rs
                        corresp="recqAPrajNMdo0x5k" type="topic">National Security</rs> Affairs
                    (Allen) to President <persName corresp="#p_RR_1">Reagan</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d188fn1">Source: Reagan Library, Robert H.
                        Lilac Files, Arms Transfer: Country Files, AT: Yugoslavia [January
                        1981–April 1981]. Secret. Sent for action. Copies were sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BG_1">Bush</persName>, Meese, Baker, and Deaver. “The
                        President has seen” is stamped at the top of the memorandum. Beneath this
                        notation, written in an unknown hand, is “approved 4/15/81.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1981-04-06">April 6, 1981</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <!--<pb facs="d188-2" n="2" type="facsimile" xml:id="d188-2"/>-->
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Confirmation of U.S. <rs corresp="rech1kSSYdYtfq0Sv" type="topic">Arms
                            Transfer Policy</rs> Toward Yugoslavia (S)</item>
                </list>
                <p>Readiness to provide <rs corresp="recoKawZ2IOcE8nyB" type="topic">military
                        assistance</rs> to Yugoslavia has been part of <rs
                        corresp="recrfy3UsY8QMsqLL" type="compound-subject">U.S. foreign policy</rs>
                    since 1948, when <persName corresp="#p_TJ_1">Tito</persName> broke with
                        <persName corresp="#p_SJ_4">Stalin</persName>. It ought to be continued, and
                    in that sense there is no disagreement with the Secretary of State’s
                    recommendation at Tab A.<note n="2" xml:id="d188fn2">Not found attached. See
                            <ref target="#d186">Document 186</ref>.</note> However, two
                    considerations may be kept in mind: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>In our <rs corresp="rech1kSSYdYtfq0Sv" type="topic">arms transfer
                                policy</rs> the criterion ought not to be solely whether a given
                            country is hostile to and/or threatened by the Soviet Union but also
                            whether in its overall foreign policy it broadly supports positions
                            taken by the United States. Yugoslavia has for many years seen itself as
                            a leader of the “non-aligned bloc” and in this capacity taken positions
                            hostile to the United States. (This holds true, for example, of its
                            position on the <rs corresp="recoGY8BsVctNF3tT" type="topic"
                                >Arab-Israeli dispute</rs>.) One cannot, of course, make <rs
                                corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu" type="topic">arms transfers</rs>
                            conditional on the recipient’s alignment with <rs
                                corresp="recrfy3UsY8QMsqLL" type="compound-subject">U.S. foreign
                                policy</rs>. But a greater sensitivity to the <hi rend="italic"
                                >general</hi>
                            <rs corresp="rectqbCKMJaN5yPfG" type="topic">foreign policy</rs> line of
                            a given country instead of a narrow focus on its <rs
                                corresp="recW6DpFu8d7ioWcO" type="compound-subject">relations</rs>
                            vis-a-vis Moscow would not be amiss.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>While Yugoslavia in theory has a great deal of interest in U.S. <rs
                                corresp="recdePus5H4DpFYc9" type="topic">arms</rs>, in practice it
                            has not been eager to acquire them for fear of annoying the Russians.
                            Actual <rs corresp="rec9ptkWICFUk7Mvu" type="topic">arms transfers</rs>
                            to Yugoslavia over the past several years have been lilliputian: in
                                <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1979 equipment deliveries
                            amounted to $354,000 and in <gloss target="#t_FY_1">FY</gloss> 1980 to
                            $636,000. (S)</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p rend="sectiontitleital">RECOMMENDATION</p>
                <p>That you approve the continuance of the present policy.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d188fn3">The “Approve” option was checked.</note>
                </p>
            </div>
